content:
Another campaign promise broken?  

While this had been a campaign pledge Trump vowed to fulfill on "Day One," today's move is not a complete surprise. the White House has long since signaled that it would hold off on the move to allow space for negotiations over a possible peace deal.  The president was convinced by Jared, McMaster and others to keep that chip as leverage. 

In fact,  even before POTUS visited Israel last week, senior administration officials said he would be extending the waiver. 

“Right now we don’t have any plans to do anything that dramatic in that regard,” one official said regarding a possible move to the embassy. 
 
“The president said very clearly during the campaign that he believes the capital of Israel is where the embassy should be, but because we’re having great conversations with everyone right now we don’t think it would be a time to do that, so we don’t plan to do that on this trip.”
 
“We don’t set a script and say follow that script all the way to the end.  It’s more of an improv deal where what you’re doing is you’re constantly readjusting as more information comes.  So you know, he’s a business guy and the way business people will think is that you have a thesis, you have an idea, you start a conversation you start discussions, and what he’s done is a lot of listening… You listen and you keep adjusting you plan and you try different things until you kind of get the sense for what works, but you don’t just take a plan and try to jam it down something.”

This is becoming comical -- don't leave me alone w him!!! 

WASHINGTON — The day after President Trump asked James B. Comey, the F.B.I. director, to end an investigation into his former national security adviser, Mr. Comey confronted Attorney General Jeff Sessions and said he did not want to be left alone again with the president, according to current and former law enforcement officials.
Mr. Comey believed Mr. Sessions should protect the F.B.I. from White House influence, the officials said, and pulled him aside after a meeting in February to tell him that private interactions between the F.B.I. director and the president were inappropriate. But Mr. Sessions could not guarantee that the president would not try to talk to Mr. Comey alone again, the officials said.

Statement from President Donald J. Trump
 
Today's unanimous Supreme Court decision is a clear victory for our national security.  It allows the travel suspension for the six terror-prone countries and the refugee suspension to become largely effective.

As President, I cannot allow people into our country who want to do us harm.  I want people who can love the United States and all of its citizens, and who will be hardworking and productive. 
 
My number one responsibility as Commander in Chief is to keep the American people safe.  Today's ruling allows me to use an important tool for protecting our Nation's homeland.  I am also particularly gratified that the Supreme Court’s decision was 9-0.
